====================================================
TASK 2: WEBSITE DESIGN
====================================================

2.1 Design inspiration research

Website 1: Awwwards portfolio examples (general reference)
URL: https://www.awwwards.com/websites/portfolio/
Thoughts:
- Strong visual hierarchy with a clear hero section.
- Minimal navigation that remains readable over imagery.
- Good balance between artwork presentation and whitespace.

Website 2: Behance portfolio pages
URL: https://www.behance.net/
Thoughts:
- Grid-based portfolio presentation is effective for multiple artworks.
- Card layouts help viewers scan quickly.
- Calls to action should be clear and repeated.

Website 3: Tate artist pages
URL: https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists
Thoughts:
- Informative structure for biography and context.
- Typography and contrast are readable and accessible.
- Navigation categories can be reused for artist + shop workflows.

2.2 Visual direction and design decisions

- Genre selected: Contemporary urban visual art.
- Look and feel: Warm off-white background, earthy accent color, simple gallery card layout.
- Navigation: Top-right functional unordered-list links (Home, Portfolio, Shop, About, Contact, Cart).
- Brand placement: Artist name/logo at top-left on every page.
- Homepage structure:
  1) Centered heading
  2) Centered featured image
  3) Centered button (View Gallery / Browse)
  4) Centered introduction/description (Lorum ipsum placeholder text)
- Footer structure (consistent across pages):
  - Center: copyright and update date
  - Right: contact details
  - Far right: social media links
- Consistency: same header/footer, type scale, spacing, and button style on all pages.
- Device support: optimized at 1080px width and adapted for 480px width without horizontal scrolling.

2.3 Wireframe and mock-up notes

- Wireframe approach used in code structure:
  - Header (logo + nav)
  - Main content module (page-specific)
  - Footer (three information zones)
- Shop page includes at least five merchandise items.
- Product detail page includes all required metadata fields:
  ID, title, description, item type, published date, thumbnail image.
- Basket supports edit quantity and remove item using front-end JavaScript.

